This is the key piece for "why thinking mode fixes sampling parameters":

```c
float temperature = j->req.temperature;
int top_k = j->req.top_k;
float top_p = j->req.top_p;
float min_p = j->req.min_p;
if (ds4_think_mode_enabled(j->req.think_mode)) {
    temperature = DS4_DEFAULT_TEMPERATURE;
    top_k = 0;
    top_p = DS4_DEFAULT_TOP_P;
    min_p = DS4_DEFAULT_MIN_P;
}
if (in_tool_call && !dsml_decode_state_uses_payload_sampling(dsml_state)) {
    temperature = 0.0f;
}
```

So in thinking mode, the server IGNORES the client's temperature/top_p/min_p and forces the defaults (temperature=1, top_k=0, top_p=1, min_p=0.05). The reasoning is that thinking/reasoning quality requires the model's natural sampling distribution — clients shouldn't be able to crank up temperature or cut top_p during reasoning, as that would degrade the chain of thought.

Also: when in a tool call (DSML payload) but not using payload sampling, it forces temperature=0 (greedy) for deterministic syntax.

Now let me look at the CLI's main generation loop (run_sampled_generation around line 477) and the REPL loop (around 1128-1160) to confirm the CLI flow. Let me read ds4_cli.c around 460-500 and 1100-1170.

